# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: counting-complexity
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] In computational complexity theory and computability theory, a **counting problem** is a type of computational problem that is obtained by strengthening a decision problem.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] For example, the SAT problem asks: "Given a Boolean formula, is there a truth-value assignment such that it evaluates to True?".
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] The corresponding counting problem, called #SAT, asks: "Given a Boolean formula, how many truth-value assignments are there such that it evaluates to True?".
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] And in general, the counting problem corresponding to a decision problem X is called #X, where # is the number sign.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] Counting complexity techniques have significant applications in clarifying the relation between complexity classes of P, NP, PH, etc, in circuit complexity, and in interactive proof systems.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] Let *R* be a search problem, formalised as a binary relation $R(x,y)$ .
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] That is, given a problem instance x , one can proposed solutions. $R(x,y)$ is true iff y is an *admissible* solution to the problem instance.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] That is, it counts the total number of admissible solutions.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] This is a function problem, not a decision problem.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] In order to conform to the standard format in computational complexity theory, we use the standard trick of converting a function problem to a decision problem, using the graph of the function.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] That is, it is the set of all points on or below the curve of $c_{R}(x)$ .
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] While it appears that computing $c_{R}(x)$ is harder than deciding whether some point $(x,y)$ belongs to $\#R$ , in fact $c_{R}$ can be Cook-reduced to $\#R$ using binary search on the value of $c_{R}(x)$ , provided that $c_{R}(x)$ is bounded by $O(2^{{\mathsf {poly}}(|x|)})$ .
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] Concretely, one tests with $(x,0),(x,1),\dots ,(x,2^{n}),\dots ,(x,2^{n^{2}}),\dots$ until one finds an element not in $\#R$ , then backtracks to pinpoint the exact value of $c_{R}(x)$ .
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] In particular, $c_{R}(x)$ must be bounded by $O(2^{{\mathsf {poly}}(|x|)})$ if it is **FP**, that is, computable in polynomial time by a Turing machine, since otherwise the machine will not have enough time to produce the full output.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] Throughout this article, we assume that $c_{R}(x)$ is FP.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] This then allows us to switch between the decision-formulation with $\#R$ and the function-formulation $c_{R}$ fluidly without further comment.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] The most important classes of counting problems is the #P class, the counting problems corresponding to the NP class of decision problems.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] An NP problem a decision problem that asks, "Given a problem instance, is there at least one solution?", and furthermore, an NP problem comes with a solution-verifier Turing machine that runs in polynomial time.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] The corresponding #P problem then asks: "Given a problem instance, how many solutions are there?".
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] More succinctly, #P counts accepting paths of an nondeterministic Turing machine running in polynomial time.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] Just as NP has NP-complete problems via many-one reductions, #P has #P-complete problems via polynomial-time parsimonious reductions.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] This reduction is reflexive and transitive.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] Some problems are ♯P-complete under polynomial-time parsimonious counting reduction, such as the #3SAT problem.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] To show this, one simply takes the standard proof that 3SAT problem is NP-complete, and note that the reduction used in the proof is already parsimonious.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] More examples are given on the Parsimonious reduction page.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] The polynomial-time many-one counting reduction is another, more lenient form of reduction.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] Counting analogs of many natural NP-complete problems are #P-complete, but the opposite is not the case: Some decision problems correspond to #P-complete counting problems, even if they are in P, or even trivially decidable.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] For example, the 01-permanent counting problem is ♯P-complete under polynomial-time many-one counting reduction.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] This problem is equivalent to counting perfect matchings in a bipartite graph.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] Deciding whether perfect matchings exist in a bipartite graph is polynomial-time by the Hopcroft–Karp algorithm.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] ModkP asks: "Given a problem instance, is the number of solutions divisible by *k*?".
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] For all k≥2, ModkP contains the graph isomorphism problem.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] Further, the graph isomorphism problem is low in ModkP.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] When *k* is prime, the set of languages low in ModkP is ModkP itself.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] It asks: "Given a problem instance, is the number of solutions even or odd?".
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] PP, or PPT is the class of decision problems solvable by a probabilistic Turing machine in polynomial time, with an error probability of less than 1/2 for all instances.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] This is equivalently defined as: "Given a positive problem instance, and a nondeterministic Turing machine in polynomial time, are more than half of the potential solutions actually correct?".
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] Note that, in order for the question to make sense, one must define the set of "potential solutions".
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] In most cases of NP problems, the set of "potential solutions" is obvious.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] For example, for the SAT problem, a problem instance is a Boolean formula $\phi$ , and the set of potential solutions is the set of boolean value assignments $V\to \{0,1\}$ , where V is the set of variables in $\phi$ .
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] The **FewP** class ("NP with few witnesses") is defined as a particular class of NP decision problems.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] Specifically, a decision problem is FewP if there exists a nondeterministic Turing machine that solves it in polynomial time, and for any problem instance x , there are at most ${\mathsf {poly}}(|x|)$ accepting paths for the machine.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] Intuitively, this is the class of decision problems that, if false, has no witnesses, and if true, has only polynomially many witnesses (thus "few").
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] Contrast this with the full class of NP problems, where if true, there could be exponentially many witnesses.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] An even more restrictive class is UP ("unambiguous NP"), the class of decision problems with at most 1 witness.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] The class is quite small, as FewP ⊆ ⊕P, which implies that FewP is low for ⊕P.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] GapP is obtained by closing #P under subtraction.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] That is, it asks: "Given a problem instance, what is the number of solutions minus the number of non-solutions?".
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] Here, the non-solutions must be taken from the set of potential solutions.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] This is defined in the same way as in the PP class.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] C=P asks: "Given a problem instance, is the gap zero?".
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] It is proven to be the complement of nondeterministic quantum polynomial-time (coNQPT).
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] This is called Toda's theorem, and it won Seinosuke Toda the Gödel prize in 1998.
[src:counting-complexity/counting-problem-complexity] There is strong evidence that many naturally occurring counting classes (PP, C=P, ModkP, etc) are strictly harder than PH, since it is proven that if they are not strictly harder than PH, then the PH collapses, which is widely considered to be unlikely.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] In computer science, a **holographic algorithm** is an algorithm that uses a holographic reduction.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] A holographic reduction is a constant-time reduction that maps solution fragments many-to-many such that the sum of the solution fragments remains unchanged.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] These concepts were introduced by Leslie Valiant, who called them *holographic* because "their effect can be viewed as that of producing interference patterns among the solution fragments".
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] The algorithms are unrelated to laser holography, except metaphorically.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] Their power comes from the mutual cancellation of many contributions to a sum, analogous to the interference patterns in a hologram.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] Holographic algorithms have been used to find polynomial-time solutions to problems without such previously known solutions for special cases of satisfiability, vertex cover, and other graph problems.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] They have received notable coverage due to speculation that they are relevant to the P versus NP problem and their impact on computational complexity theory.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] Although some of the general problems are #P-hard problems, the special cases solved are not themselves #P-hard, and thus do not prove FP = #P.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] Holographic algorithms have some similarities with quantum computation, but are completely classical.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] Holographic algorithms exist in the context of Holant problems, which generalize counting constraint satisfaction problems (#CSP).
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] A #CSP instance is a hypergraph *G*=(*V*,*E*) called the constraint graph.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] Each hyperedge represents a variable and each vertex v is assigned a constraint $f_{v}.$ A vertex is connected to an hyperedge if the constraint on the vertex involves the variable on the hyperedge.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] which is a sum over all variable assignments, the product of every constraint, where the inputs to the constraint $f_{v}$ are the variables on the incident hyperedges of v .
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] A Holant problem is like a #CSP except the input must be a graph, not a hypergraph.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] Restricting the class of input graphs in this way is indeed a generalization.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] Given a #CSP instance, replace each hyperedge *e* of size *s* with a vertex *v* of degree *s* with edges incident to the vertices contained in *e*.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] The constraint on *v* is the equality function of arity *s*.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] This identifies all of the variables on the edges incident to *v*, which is the same effect as the single variable on the hyperedge *e*.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] In the context of Holant problems, the expression in (1) is called the Holant after a related exponential sum introduced by Valiant.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] A standard technique in complexity theory is a many-one reduction, where an instance of one problem is reduced to an instance of another (hopefully simpler) problem.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] However, holographic reductions between two computational problems preserve the sum of solutions without necessarily preserving correspondences between solutions.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] For instance, the total number of solutions in both sets can be preserved, even though individual problems do not have matching solutions.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] The sum can also be weighted, rather than simply counting the number of solutions, using linear basis vectors.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] It is convenient to consider holographic reductions on bipartite graphs.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] A general graph can always be transformed it into a bipartite graph while preserving the Holant value.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] This is done by replacing each edge in the graph by a path of length 2, which is also known as the 2-stretch of the graph.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] To keep the same Holant value, each new vertex is assigned the binary equality constraint.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] Consider a bipartite graph *G*=(*U*,*V*,*E*) where the constraint assigned to every vertex $u\in U$ is $f_{u}$ and the constraint assigned to every vertex $v\in V$ is $f_{v}$ .
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] They essentially define the same counting problem.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] There is a 1-to-1 correspondence between the vertex covers of *G* and the independent sets of *G*.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] For any set *S* of vertices of *G*, *S* is a vertex cover in *G* if and only if the complement of *S* is an independent set in *G*.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] Thus, the number of vertex covers in *G* is exactly the same as the number of independent sets in *G*.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] The equivalence of these two counting problems can also be proved using a holographic reduction.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] For simplicity, let *G* be a 3-regular graph.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] The 2-stretch of *G* gives a bipartite graph *H*=(*U*,*V*,*E*), where *U* corresponds to the edges in *G* and *V* corresponds to the vertices in *G*.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] The Holant problem that naturally corresponds to counting the number of vertex covers in *G* is ${\text{Holant}}(H,{\text{OR}}_{2},{\text{EQUAL}}_{3}).$ The truth table of OR2 as a row vector is (0,1,1,1).
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] which is ${\text{Holant}}(H,{\text{NAND}}_{2},{\text{EQUAL}}_{3}),$ the Holant problem that naturally corresponds to counting the number of independent sets in *G*.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] As with any type of reduction, a holographic reduction does not, by itself, yield a polynomial time algorithm.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] In order to get a polynomial time algorithm, the problem being reduced to must also have a polynomial time algorithm.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] Valiant's original application of holographic algorithms used a holographic reduction to a problem where every constraint is realizable by matchgates, which he had just proved is tractable by a further reduction to counting the number of perfect matchings in a planar graph.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] The latter problem is tractable by the FKT algorithm, which dates to the 1960s.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] Soon after, Valiant found holographic algorithms with reductions to matchgates for #7Pl-Rtw-Mon-3CNF and #7Pl-3/2Bip-VC.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] These problems may appear somewhat contrived, especially with respect to the modulus.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] Both problems were already known to be #P-hard when ignoring the modulus and Valiant supplied proofs of #P-hardness modulo 2, which also used holographic reductions.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] Valiant found these two problems by a computer search that looked for problems with holographic reductions to matchgates.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] After several years of developing (what is known as) matchgate signature theory, Jin-Yi Cai and Pinyan Lu were able to explain the existence of Valiant's two accidental algorithms.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] These two problems are just special cases of two much larger families of problems: #2k-1Pl-Rtw-Mon-kCNF and #2k-1Pl-k/2Bip-VC for any positive integer *k*.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] The modulus 7 is just the third Mersenne number and Cai and Lu showed that these types of problems with parameter *k* can be solved in polynomial time exactly when the modulus is the *k*th Mersenne number by using holographic reductions to matchgates and the Chinese remainder theorem.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] Around the same time, Jin-Yi Cai, Pinyan Lu and Mingji Xia gave the first holographic algorithm that did not reduce to a problem that is tractable by matchgates.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] Instead, they reduced to a problem that is tractable by Fibonacci gates, which are symmetric constraints whose truth tables satisfy a recurrence relation similar to one that defines the Fibonacci numbers.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] They also used holographic reductions to prove that certain counting problems are #P-hard.
[src:counting-complexity/holographic-algorithm] Since then, holographic reductions have been used extensively as ingredients in both polynomial time algorithms and proofs of #P-hardness.
[src:counting-complexity/p] In computational complexity theory, the complexity class **#P** (pronounced "sharp P" or, sometimes "number P" or "hash P") is the set of the counting problems associated with the decision problems in the set **NP**.
[src:counting-complexity/p] More formally, **#P** is the class of function problems of the form "compute *f*(*x*)", where *f* is the number of accepting paths of a nondeterministic Turing machine running in polynomial time.
[src:counting-complexity/p] Unlike most well-known complexity classes, it is not a class of decision problems but a class of function problems.
[src:counting-complexity/p] The most difficult, representative problems of this class are #P-complete.
[src:counting-complexity/p] Corresponding **#P** function problems ask "how many" rather than "are there any".
[src:counting-complexity/p] Clearly, a **#P** problem must be at least as hard as the corresponding **NP** problem.
[src:counting-complexity/p] If it's easy to count answers, then it must be easy to tell whether there are any answers—just count them and see whether the count is greater than zero.
[src:counting-complexity/p] Some of these problems, such as root counting, are easy enough to be in FP, while others are #P-complete.
[src:counting-complexity/p] One consequence of Toda's theorem is that a polynomial-time machine with a **#P** oracle (**P****#P**) can solve all problems in **PH**, the entire polynomial hierarchy.
[src:counting-complexity/p] In fact, the polynomial-time machine only needs to make one **#P** query to solve any problem in **PH**.
[src:counting-complexity/p] This is an indication of the extreme difficulty of solving **#P**-complete problems exactly.
[src:counting-complexity/p] Surprisingly, some **#P** problems that are believed to be difficult correspond to easy (for example linear-time) **P** problems.
[src:counting-complexity/p] For more information on this, see #P-complete.
[src:counting-complexity/p] The closest decision problem class to **#P** is **PP**, which asks whether a majority (more than half) of the computation paths accept.
[src:counting-complexity/p] This finds the most significant bit in the **#P** problem answer.
[src:counting-complexity/p] The decision problem class **⊕P** (pronounced "Parity-P") instead asks for the least significant bit of the **#P** answer.
[src:counting-complexity/p] equals the size of the set containing all of the polynomial-size certificates).
[src:counting-complexity/p] The complexity class **#P** was first defined by Leslie Valiant in a 1979 article on the computation of the permanent of a square matrix, in which he proved that permanent is #P-complete.
[src:counting-complexity/p] Larry Stockmeyer has proved that for every #P problem P there exists a randomized algorithm using an oracle for SAT, which given an instance a of P and $\epsilon >0$ returns with high probability a number x such that $(1-\epsilon )P(a)\leq x\leq (1+\epsilon )P(a)$ .
[src:counting-complexity/p] The runtime of the algorithm is polynomial in a and $1/\epsilon$ .
[src:counting-complexity/p] The algorithm is based on the leftover hash lemma.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] In linear algebra, the **permanent** of a square matrix is a function of the matrix similar to the determinant.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] The permanent, as well as the determinant, is a polynomial in the entries of the matrix.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] Both are special cases of a more general function of a matrix called the immanant.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] The sum here extends over all elements *σ* of the symmetric group *S**n*; i.e., over all permutations of the numbers 1, 2, ..., *n*.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] The definition of the permanent of *A* differs from that of the determinant of *A* in that the signatures of the permutations are not taken into account.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] The permanent of a matrix A is denoted per *A*, perm *A*, or Per *A*, sometimes with parentheses around the argument.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] Minc uses Per(*A*) for the permanent of rectangular matrices, and per(*A*) when *A* is a square matrix.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] The word, *permanent*, originated with Cauchy in 1812 as "fonctions symétriques permanentes" for a related type of function, and was used by Muir and Metzler in the modern, more specific, sense.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] If one views the permanent as a map that takes *n* vectors as arguments, then it is a multilinear map and it is symmetric (meaning that any order of the vectors results in the same permanent).
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] Laplace's expansion by minors for computing the determinant along a row, column or diagonal extends to the permanent by ignoring all signs.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] where $B_{i,j}$ is the entry of the *i*th row and the *j*th column of *B*, and ${\textstyle M_{i,j}}$ is the permanent of the submatrix obtained by removing the *i*th row and the *j*th column of *B*.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] On the other hand, the basic multiplicative property of determinants is not valid for permanents.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] Unlike the determinant, the permanent has no easy geometrical interpretation; it is mainly used in combinatorics, in treating boson Green's functions in quantum field theory, and in determining state probabilities of boson sampling systems.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] However, it has two graph-theoretic interpretations: as the sum of weights of cycle covers of a directed graph, and as the sum of weights of perfect matchings in a bipartite graph.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] The permanent arises naturally in the study of the symmetric tensor power of Hilbert spaces.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] In particular, for a Hilbert space H , let $\vee ^{k}H$ denote the k th symmetric tensor power of H , which is the space of symmetric tensors.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] Note in particular that $\vee ^{k}H$ is spanned by the symmetric products of elements in H .
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] Any square matrix $A=(a_{ij})_{i,j=1}^{n}$ can be viewed as the adjacency matrix of a weighted directed graph on vertex set $V=\{1,2,\dots ,n\}$ , with $a_{ij}$ representing the weight of the arc from vertex *i* to vertex *j*.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] A cycle cover of a weighted directed graph is a collection of vertex-disjoint directed cycles in the digraph that covers all vertices in the graph.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] Thus, each vertex *i* in the digraph has a unique "successor" $\sigma (i)$ in the cycle cover, and so $\sigma$ represents a permutation on *V*.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] Conversely, any permutation $\sigma$ on *V* corresponds to a cycle cover with arcs from each vertex *i* to vertex $\sigma (i)$ .
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] A square matrix $A=(a_{ij})$ can also be viewed as the adjacency matrix of a bipartite graph which has vertices $x_{1},x_{2},\dots ,x_{n}$ on one side and $y_{1},y_{2},\dots ,y_{n}$ on the other side, with $a_{ij}$ representing the weight of the edge from vertex $x_{i}$ to vertex $y_{j}$ .
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] The answers to many counting questions can be computed as permanents of matrices that only have 0 and 1 as entries.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] Let Ω(*n*, *k*) be the class of all (0, 1)-matrices of order *n* with each row and column sum equal to *k*.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] Every matrix *A* in this class has perm(*A*) > 0.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] The incidence matrices every finite projective plane is in the class Ω(*n*2 + *n* + 1, *n* + 1) for some integer *n* > 1.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] The permanents corresponding to the smallest projective planes have been calculated.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] Let *Z* be the incidence matrix of the projective plane with *n* = 2, the Fano plane.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] Remarkably, perm(*Z*) = 24 = |det (*Z*)|, the absolute value of the determinant of *Z*.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] Permanents can also be used to calculate the number of permutations with restricted (prohibited) positions.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] Then perm(*A*) is equal to the number of permutations of the *n*-set that satisfy all the restrictions.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] For an *n*×*n* (0, 1)-matrix, the permanent may be equivalently described as the number of ways of placing *n* mutually non-attacking rooks on the *n*×*n* chessboard so that no rook is at a position where the matrix has a 0 entry.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] The Bregman–Minc inequality, conjectured by H.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] Brégman in 1973, gives an upper bound for the permanent of an *n* × *n* (0, 1)-matrix.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] In 1926, Van der Waerden conjectured that the minimum permanent among all *n* × *n* doubly stochastic matrices is *n*!/*n**n*, achieved by the matrix for which all entries are equal to 1/*n*.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] Proofs of this conjecture were published in 1980 by B.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] Egorychev's proof is an application of the Alexandrov–Fenchel inequality.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] For this work, Egorychev and Falikman won the Fulkerson Prize in 1982.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] The naïve approach, using the definition, of computing permanents is computationally infeasible even for relatively small matrices.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] One of the fastest known algorithms is due to H.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] Ryser's method is based on an inclusion–exclusion formula that can be given as follows: Let $A_{k}$ be obtained from *A* by deleting *k* columns, let $P(A_{k})$ be the product of the row-sums of $A_{k}$ , and let $\Sigma _{k}$ be the sum of the values of $P(A_{k})$ over all possible $A_{k}$ .
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] The permanent is believed to be more difficult to compute than the determinant.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] While the determinant can be computed in polynomial time by Gaussian elimination, Gaussian elimination cannot be used to compute the permanent.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] Moreover, computing the permanent of a (0,1)-matrix is #P-complete.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] Thus, if the permanent can be computed in polynomial time by any method, then **FP = #P**, which is an even stronger statement than P = NP.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] When the entries of *A* are nonnegative, however, the permanent can be computed approximately in probabilistic polynomial time, up to an error of $\varepsilon M$ , where M is the value of the permanent and $\varepsilon >0$ is arbitrary.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] The permanent of a certain set of positive semidefinite matrices is NP-hard to approximate within any subexponential factor.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] If further conditions on the spectrum are imposed, the permanent can be approximated in probabilistic polynomial time: the best achievable error of this approximation is $\varepsilon {\sqrt {M}}$ ( M is again the value of the permanent).
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] The hardness in these instances is closely linked with difficulty of simulating boson sampling experiments.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] Another way to view permanents is via multivariate generating functions.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] Let $A=(a_{ij})$ be a square matrix of order *n*.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] The permanent function can be generalized to apply to non-square matrices.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] Indeed, several authors make this the definition of a permanent and consider the restriction to square matrices a special case.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] Ryser's computational result for permanents also generalizes.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] If *A* is an *m* × *n* matrix with *m* ≤ *n*, let $A_{k}$ be obtained from *A* by deleting *k* columns, let $P(A_{k})$ be the product of the row-sums of $A_{k}$ , and let $\sigma _{k}$ be the sum of the values of $P(A_{k})$ over all possible $A_{k}$ .
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] The generalization of the definition of a permanent to non-square matrices allows the concept to be used in a more natural way in some applications.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] The incidence matrix of this collection of subsets is an *m* × *n* (0,1)-matrix *A*.
[src:counting-complexity/permanent-mathematics] The number of systems of distinct representatives (SDR's) of this collection is perm(*A*).
[src:counting-complexity/toda-s-theorem] The theorem states that the entire polynomial hierarchy PH is contained in PPP; this implies a closely related statement, that PH is contained in P#P.
[src:counting-complexity/toda-s-theorem] An analogous result in the complexity theory over the reals (in the sense of Blum–Shub–Smale real Turing machines) was proved by Saugata Basu and Thierry Zell in 2010 and a complex analogue of Toda's theorem was proved by Saugata Basu in 2011.
[src:counting-complexity/toda-s-theorem] A more leisurely proof is in the textbook Arora & Barak 2009.
[src:counting-complexity/valiant-vazirani-theorem] The **Valiant–Vazirani theorem** is a theorem in computational complexity theory stating that if there is a polynomial time algorithm for Unambiguous-SAT, then NP = RP.
[src:counting-complexity/valiant-vazirani-theorem] It was proven by Leslie Valiant and Vijay Vazirani in their paper titled *NP is as easy as detecting unique solutions* published in 1986.
[src:counting-complexity/valiant-vazirani-theorem] The Valiant–Vazirani theorem implies that the Boolean satisfiability problem, which is NP-complete, remains a computationally hard problem even if the input instances are promised to have at most one satisfying assignment.
[src:counting-complexity/valiant-vazirani-theorem] Unambiguous-SAT is the promise problem of deciding whether a given Boolean formula that has at most one satisfying assignment is unsatisfiable or has exactly one satisfying assignment.
[src:counting-complexity/valiant-vazirani-theorem] In the first case, an algorithm for Unambiguous-SAT should reject, and in the second it should accept the formula.
[src:counting-complexity/valiant-vazirani-theorem] If the formula has more than one satisfying assignment, then there is no condition on the behavior of the algorithm.
[src:counting-complexity/valiant-vazirani-theorem] The promise problem Unambiguous-SAT can be decided by a nondeterministic Turing machine that has at most one accepting computation path, thus it belongs to the promise version of the complexity class UP (the class UP as such is only defined for languages).
[src:counting-complexity/valiant-vazirani-theorem] The idea of the reduction is to successively intersect the solution space of the formula *F* with *n* random linear hyperplanes in $\mathbb {F} _{2}^{n}$ .
[src:counting-complexity/valiant-vazirani-theorem] As a consequence (not needed for the **NP** = **RP** argument, but of independent interest), if we choose one of the *Gi* at random, we obtain a randomized reduction with one-sided error from SAT to Unambiguous-SAT that succeeds with probability at least Ω(1/*n*).
[src:counting-complexity/valiant-vazirani-theorem] That is, if *F* is unsatisfiable, the output formula is always unsatisfiable, and if *F* is satisfiable, then the output formula has a unique satisfying assignment with probability Ω(1/*n*).
[src:counting-complexity/valiant-vazirani-theorem] Now, assuming Unambiguous-SAT is solvable by a polynomial time algorithm *A*, we obtain an **RP** algorithm for SAT by running *A* on *Gi* for each *i* ≤ *n*.
[src:counting-complexity/valiant-vazirani-theorem] If *F* is unsatisfiable, then *A* rejects all *Gi* as they are unsatisfiable, whereas if *F* is satisfiable, then *A* accepts some *Gi* with probability at least 1/4.
[src:counting-complexity/valiant-vazirani-theorem] More generally, this argument shows unconditionally that **NP** is included in **RPpromiseUP**.
[src:counting-complexity/valiant-vazirani-theorem] An alternative proof is based on the isolation lemma by Mulmuley, Vazirani, and Vazirani.
[src:counting-complexity/valiant-vazirani-theorem] They consider a more general setting, and applied to the setting here this gives an isolation probability of only $\Omega (1/n^{8})$ .
